\chapter{Introduction}
Our project is an AI-driven biomechanical analysis tool that uses Human Pose Estimation and machine learning to autonomously evaluate and correct cricket batting techniques using standard 2D video. By benchmarking a player's spatial kinematics against professional datasets and utilizing Generative AI for real-time feedback, the system democratizes elite-level sports analytics for amateur players without the need for expensive motion-capture labs.

\section{Introduction}
In the field of modern sports analytics, the precise analysis of the biomechanics of an individual is of utmost importance in the development of the sportsperson as well as the improvement of their techniques. In the actual environment, amateur sportspeople often tend to develop technical flaws in their game, as they are not provided with instant, precise, and objective feedback. In the case of professional cricket organizations, the most advanced motion analysis labs with the ability to mathematically analyze the biomechanics of the player are used. These traditional methods of analyzing the biomechanics of the player are highly expensive, invasive, and completely beyond the reach of schools in the local area.
In order to bridge this technological as well as economic gap, this project aims at developing a novel AI-based "Posture-Based Technique Feedback System for Cricket Batting." Using the highly efficient "Triple Model Artificial Intelligence" framework, the system is able to provide the benefits of the most advanced motion analysis labs to the amateur sportspeople of the local area by extracting the spatial kinematics of the player directly from the 2D video input, utilizing the highly efficient computer vision algorithms of Google MediaPipe, the supervised machine learning algorithm of Random Forest with the UCF101 dataset, as well as the cognitive reasoning of the highly efficient OpenAI GPT-4o algorithm, creating an efficient "Sense-Verify-Advise" framework that is highly efficient in eliminating the observation bias of the individual, allowing the system to automatically classify the complex batting techniques of the player.

\section{Motivation}
The underlying motivation for choosing this particular theme was rooted in the technological and financial disparity that exists in sports technology in the modern world. At the highest echelon, cricket boards around the world have invested in state-of-the-art, multi-million-dollar motion capture facilities that incorporate physical sensors (Vicon) for the mathematical analysis of the player's biomechanics. However, at the grassroots level, local academies, schools, and amateur players are completely omitted from this data-driven world due to the underlying financial constraints. This has caused amateur players to develop poor technical skills, as they are forced to solely depend on human observation without any objective feedback mechanism in their training sessions. This project was chosen with the underlying objective of bridging this technological gap. The underlying motivation for choosing this project was rooted in the desire to create a low-cost software-only artificial intelligence system that could bridge the technological gap in sports technology, enabling local players and coaches to access precise, reproducible, and automated biomechanical feedback, which was previously only accessible to international sports professionals.The primary catalyst for this project was observing the severe limitations of traditional hardware-based motion capture. Currently, elite analysis requires players to wear physical, invasive sensors (such as IMU suits) in multi-million-dollar laboratories. We were deeply motivated to break down this financial and logistical paywall by engineering a completely markerless, software-driven alternative that empowers grassroots players with the same level of analytical precision.

\section{Problem Definition}
In amateur cricket, the dominant trend of repeating technical kinematic errors due to the absence of objective data-driven feedback mechanisms has been noted. The underlying concern here is the absence of a low-cost, automated system with the ability to process high-speed athletic movements captured by conventional 2D video technology. The currently available biomechanical feedback tools offer a binary constraint, either being basic video recording tools with no computational correction capabilities or being hardware-dependent tools with the need to purchase expensive hardware sensors and complex infrared camera systems.
This emphasis on hardware tools poses a massive logistical challenge. The hardware tools used to record motion are prohibitively expensive for amateur cricket academies, and the need to physically attach hardware tools such as IMUs to the batsman during live net practice fundamentally inhibits the natural movement of the batsman. Therefore, a pressing need exists for a passive solution with the ability to autonomously recognize spatial kinematics and structural technique with consumer-grade cameras.

\section{Objectives}
The main objective of conducting this project is to develop an artificial intelligence-based real-time posture analysis tool that provides the user with feedback regarding the techniques they are using while playing various sports like cricket and football by applying the concept of computer vision-based pose estimation models. The main objective of developing this tool is to enable the user to enhance their performance while playing sports by accurately identifying the key points of the user and the key points of the professional players, thereby enabling the user to correct their techniques while playing various sports without the fear of getting injured by applying the concept of Python-based frameworks like Streamlit and Flask.

\section{Scope of the project}
The scope of this project centers on the development of a specialized computer vision application designed to analyze and enhance cricket batting techniques through automated posture feedback. Leveraging the MediaPipe pose estimation framework and Python-based libraries like OpenCV, the system identifies thirty-three distinct skeletal landmarks to evaluate critical body alignments, such as head position, elbow elevation, and knee flexion during specific shots like the forward defense. The functional boundary of the project is strictly defined by human kinetic analysis, providing real-time visual overlays that indicate corrective measures for the batsman. While the system excels at detecting postural deviations in batting, it deliberately excludes the tracking of ball trajectories, bowling actions, or complex fielding maneuvers. Designed as a lightweight tool for student-athletes and coaches, the project aims to provide a high-precision, cost-effective alternative to expensive wearable sensors, making professional-grade technical analysis accessible through a standard camera interface.

