\chapter{Literature Survey}
In this chapter, a detailed literature survey of the existing research done in the particular domain of sports analytics, focusing on cricket posture analysis as well as stroke classification, will be presented. This will provide us with an idea of the different methodologies that have been employed, ranging from traditional feature-based detection approaches to more sophisticated deep learning approaches. This will provide us with an insight into the existing gaps of real-time feedback systems, which will, in turn, help us understand the need for our proposed system of posture-based detection.
\section{Paper [1] : Pose‑Based Stroke Classification}
Siddiqui et al. (2023) investigated the automated identification of cricket strokes by analyzing human pose landmarks. Their methodology employed the MediaPipe framework for precise, real-time joint detection, seamlessly extracting spatial coordinates. These biomechanical features were then processed through machine learning classifiers to successfully categorize various batting strokes. While this model demonstrated commendable classification accuracy and was validated against a highly detailed, well-prepared dataset, its overall utility remains fundamentally constrained. The system’s scope is limited strictly to stroke identification. Consequently, it lacks the critical analytical depth required to evaluate technical flaws or provide actionable posture correction feedback to athletes aiming to improve.
\section{Paper [2] : Feature‑Based Shot Detection}
Moodley and van der Haar (2019) have provided a system that recognizes cricket strokes by extracting basic visual features of the human body instead of relying on intricate mapping of the human skeleton. The basic methodology of this system involves extracting specific geometric features from the player’s bat and torso, which are then passed to a machine learning classifier to determine the type of shot that has been executed. This basic methodology, while highly efficient and responsive, possessed one of the biggest analytical drawbacks. The complete absence of joint tracking meant that the player’s basic biomechanical posture could not be analyzed. Therefore, while this system could be highly effective in terms of basic shot recognition, it could never be used to provide the kind of technical feedback that could be used to correct posture.
\section{Paper [3] : ML‑Based Stroke Recognition}
Devanandan et al. (2021) explored the application of classical machine learning techniques to address the challenge of automated cricket stroke recognition. Their proposed approach utilized a Random Forest classification algorithm trained extensively on visually engineered features extracted entirely from static images. This specific methodology proved highly advantageous for researchers working with smaller datasets, as it significantly reduced training times and maintained lower overall computational costs compared to deep learning alternatives. However, the reliance on static, two-dimensional images introduced a critical limitation. By evaluating shots as isolated frames, the system completely ignored crucial motion timing, weight distribution shifts, and sequential movement information. Because executing a proper cricket stroke is inherently dynamic, relying solely on static spatial analysis prevents the model from capturing the fluid mechanics of the swing, limiting its potential as a comprehensive coaching or technique refinement tool.
\section{Paper [4] : Deep Learning for Motion Sequences}
The study done by Bandara and Bačić in the year 2020 was a major leap forward for sports analytics, as the authors employed deep learning techniques for analyzing sequences of continuous movement of the ball during a cricket stroke. The collective method, as employed in this study, was able to process video sequences for training an LSTM network, as opposed to relying on individual frames of the video, which might not have captured the transitions of movement of the ball with sufficient accuracy. Thus, with the increased power of sports analytics came a number of challenges as well. The first challenge was that the LSTM network required a large video dataset for training the network. In addition to this, though the network was able to attain high accuracy levels for the identification of different strokes, it was not able to provide any feedback to the athlete.

\section{Paper [5] : Early Automated Shot Detection}
Representing one of the earliest foundational attempts at automated sports analysis, Lazarescu et al. (1999) explored the automatic detection and classification of cricket shots using early computer vision techniques. Their pioneering methodology relied primarily on analyzing global camera motion parameters and extracting basic visual cues from broadcast footage, rather than focusing directly on player biomechanics. While this early work was highly innovative and successfully introduced several core conceptual frameworks for automated cricket analysis, practical implementation revealed severe limitations. The system suffered from notably low overall classification accuracy when tested on diverse footage. Additionally, the pipeline required significant manual intervention and pre-processing steps to function correctly. Because of these heavy computational burdens and the lack of automated tracking, the methodology was ultimately deemed entirely unsuitable for modern, real-time application or in-game player analysis.
