\chapter{Proposed System}
The Proposed System utilizes a "Triple-Model" AI architecture titled "Sense-Verify-Advise" to democratize elite-level cricket coaching through accessible computer vision. This tiered structure begins with a Perception Layer where Google MediaPipe extracts 33 distinct 3D skeletal landmarks(99 points) from raw 2D video frames to perform high-frequency kinematic mapping. These spatial coordinates are then passed to a Validation Layer, which utilizes a Random Forest classifier trained on the UCF101 dataset to benchmark amateur form against professional signatures and identify technical deviations such as head-dropping or lead-knee collapse. Finally, the Cognitive Layer integrates the OpenAI GPT-4o API to translate complex biometric scalars into concise, human-centric coaching heuristics, which are delivered via a FastAPI backend and displayed on a modern "Glassmorphism" styled dashboard.
\\
It is designed as an intelligent cricket posture detection and analysis platform that leverages advancements in computer vision and machine learning to evaluate batting techniques from video input. Unlike traditional coaching methods that rely heavily on manual observation and subjective judgment, this system introduces an automated, data-driven approach to analyzing player performance. By integrating a web-based interface with a robust backend and a trained machine learning model, the system provides a seamless environment where users can upload videos of cricket shots and receive detailed biomechanical feedback.
\\
At its core, the system focuses on understanding human body movement through pose estimation techniques. It identifies key skeletal landmarks from video frames and uses these landmarks to compute critical joint angles, particularly the elbow angle, which plays a significant role in determining the type and quality of a cricket shot. The system not only classifies the shot but also evaluates posture correctness and provides actionable feedback. Additionally, it generates a structured PDF report, making the analysis portable and useful for training purposes.

\section{Methodology}
The Methodology of the system follows a structured "Detection-Analysis-Feedback" computational pipeline designed to transform raw video data into actionable biomechanical insights. The process initiates at the Perception Layer, where Google MediaPipe extracts 33 distinct 3D skeletal landmarks from 2D video frames to perform high-frequency kinematic mapping. These spatial coordinates are then ingested by the Validation Layer, which utilizes the Law of Cosines to calculate precise joint angles while a Random Forest classifier, trained on the UCF101 dataset, benchmarks the user's form against professional athletic signatures to identify technical deviations like head-dropping or lead-knee collapse. Finally, the Cognitive Layer leverages the OpenAI GPT-4o API to perform zero-shot inference, translating complex biometric scalars into human-centric coaching heuristics that are delivered via a FastAPI backend and displayed on a "Glassmorphism" styled dashboard.
\\
The methodology adopted in this system follows a structured pipeline that transforms raw video input into meaningful analytical insights. It combines techniques from computer vision, machine learning, and biomechanical analysis to evaluate cricket shots. Each stage of the methodology is carefully designed to ensure accurate detection, efficient processing, and meaningful output generation.

