The system architecture of the Cricket Posture Detection System follows a layered and modular design, where each component performs a specific role in transforming raw video input into meaningful analytical output. The architecture is divided into four primary layers: the user layer, the presentation layer, the application layer, and the data processing layer. These layers interact seamlessly to ensure smooth data flow and efficient processing.
At the highest level, the user interacts with the system through a web interface, which communicates with the backend server. The backend orchestrates the entire workflow by invoking different processing modules such as video analysis, pose detection, and machine learning classification. The results are then stored and presented back to the user in a structured format.
The user layer represents the external entity interacting with the system. Users access the system through a web-based interface built using HTML, Tailwind CSS, and JavaScript. This frontend layer is responsible for capturing user inputs such as login credentials and video uploads. It also displays outputs including processed videos, feedback, and downloadable reports.
The frontend communicates with the backend using HTTP requests, specifically through RESTful APIs. It ensures that user interactions are intuitive and responsive, hiding the complexity of backend processing while providing a smooth experience.
The backend layer is implemented using FastAPI and acts as the central controller of the system. It receives requests from the frontend, validates user authentication, and manages session handling using cookies. Once a video is uploaded, the backend stores it temporarily and triggers the analysis pipeline.

This layer is responsible for coordinating different modules, including video processing, pose detection, machine learning inference, and report generation. It also formats the final response, which includes the processed video URL, feedback data, and report link, and sends it back to the frontend.



\section{Module Description}
The system utilizes cricket shot videos sourced from datasets such as UCF101, which contain various sports-related video clips. These videos serve as the foundation for training the machine learning model. During preprocessing, videos are read frame by frame using OpenCV, and each frame is converted into RGB format to ensure compatibility with the MediaPipe pose detection model.
Noise reduction and normalization techniques are implicitly handled through the pose detection framework, ensuring that only relevant skeletal information is extracted. This step is crucial in preparing the data for feature extraction and subsequent analysis.
The Cricket Posture Detection System is designed using a modular architecture in which each component is responsible for a specific functionality within the overall workflow. This modular approach not only simplifies system design and implementation but also enhances scalability and maintainability. Each module operates independently while contributing to the complete pipeline of video analysis, posture detection, and feedback generation. The following sections describe each module in detail.
\subsection{Pose Detection and Feature Extraction}
Pose detection is carried out using the MediaPipe library, which identifies 33 key landmarks on the human body. These landmarks include joints such as the shoulders, elbows, wrists, hips, knees, and ankles. Each landmark is represented by three coordinates: x, y, and z, indicating its position in three-dimensional space.
The extracted landmarks are then converted into numerical feature vectors by flattening the coordinate values into a single array. This transformation enables the data to be used as input for machine learning models. The consistency and accuracy of these features play a critical role in determining the effectiveness of the system.
\subsection{Angle Calculation and Biomechanical Analysis}
A key aspect of the methodology is the calculation of joint angles, particularly the elbow angle, which is computed using trigonometric functions. By considering three points corresponding to the shoulder, elbow, and wrist, the system calculates the angle formed at the elbow joint. This angle is computed for multiple frames and averaged to obtain a stable and reliable measurement.

The calculated angle is then used as a primary metric for shot classification. In addition to angle calculation, the system performs biomechanical analysis by examining posture-related parameters such as head alignment and knee balance. These parameters help identify deviations from ideal posture and contribute to generating corrective feedback.
\subsection{Model Training and Classification}
The machine learning component of the system is implemented using a Random Forest classifier. During training, the model is provided with feature vectors extracted from professional cricket shots, labeled as correct techniques. The model learns patterns associated with proper posture and shot execution.

During inference, the system uses both the trained model and rule-based logic to classify the shot. The rule-based approach relies on predefined angle thresholds to categorize shots, while the machine learning model enhances the system’s ability to generalize and recognize patterns. This hybrid approach ensures both accuracy and interpretability.
\subsection{Feedback Generation and Report Creation}
Once the shot is classified, the system generates feedback based on posture analysis. It identifies issues such as improper head positioning or imbalance in body weight and provides corrective suggestions. If no issues are detected, the system acknowledges the stability of the technique.

The final step involves generating a PDF report using the ReportLab library. This report includes details such as the type of shot, average elbow angle, number of frames analyzed, and feedback messages. The report serves as a valuable resource for players and coaches to review performance and track improvements over time.

\subsection{User Interface Module}
The user interface module serves as the primary point of interaction between the user and the system. It is developed using HTML, Tailwind CSS, and JavaScript, providing a clean, responsive, and visually engaging environment. This module allows users to register, log in, upload cricket shot videos, and view analysis results.

The interface is designed to guide the user through a structured workflow, beginning with authentication and progressing to video upload and analysis. Once the processing is complete, the interface dynamically updates to display the processed video, feedback messages, and a link to download the generated report. The use of asynchronous JavaScript ensures that the user experience remains smooth and responsive without requiring page reloads. Overall, this module plays a crucial role in ensuring usability and accessibility of the system.
\subsection{Authentication Module}
The authentication module is responsible for managing user access and ensuring secure interaction with the system. It handles user registration and login processes using credentials such as username, email, and password. The backend verifies these credentials against the database and establishes a session using cookies.

Once authenticated, the user is granted access to the dashboard and analysis features. The system maintains session persistence through HTTP cookies, allowing users to navigate the application without repeated logins. This module ensures that user-specific data, such as uploaded videos and analysis reports, are securely associated with the correct user account. By implementing basic authentication mechanisms, the system provides a foundation for secure and personalized user experiences.
\subsection{API and Backend Module (FastAPI)}
The backend module, implemented using FastAPI, acts as the central controller of the entire system. It is responsible for handling incoming requests from the frontend, processing data, and coordinating various internal modules. This module defines multiple API endpoints for functionalities such as user registration, login, video upload, and result retrieval.

When a user uploads a video, the backend receives the file, assigns it a unique identifier, and stores it in a designated directory. It then invokes the video processing and analysis pipeline. After processing, the backend constructs a response containing the processed video path, feedback data, and report link, which is sent back to the frontend. The backend also integrates with the OpenAI API to generate additional technical feedback, enhancing the quality of analysis. This module serves as the backbone of the system, ensuring smooth communication and execution of tasks.
\subsection{Video Processing Module}
The video processing module is responsible for handling raw video input and preparing it for analysis. It uses the OpenCV library to read the uploaded video frame by frame. Each frame is processed individually, allowing the system to analyze motion and posture across the entire duration of the video.
During processing, frames are converted into RGB format to make them compatible with the pose detection model. The module also writes the processed frames into a new output video file, which includes visual overlays of detected skeletal landmarks. Additionally, the module uses FFmpeg to encode the final video into a standardized format for smooth playback. This module forms the foundation of the analysis pipeline by transforming raw video data into a structured format suitable for further processing.
\subsection{Pose Detection Module}
The pose detection module utilizes the MediaPipe framework to identify and track human body landmarks in each frame of the video. MediaPipe provides a robust and efficient solution for real-time pose estimation, detecting 33 key points that represent various joints and body parts.

These landmarks include critical joints such as the shoulders, elbows, wrists, hips, and knees, which are essential for analyzing cricket batting posture. The detected landmarks are drawn onto the video frames, providing a visual representation of the player's posture. The accuracy and reliability of this module are crucial, as the extracted landmarks serve as the primary input for feature extraction and biomechanical analysis.
\subsection{Feature Extraction Module}
The feature extraction module converts the detected pose landmarks into a numerical format suitable for analysis and machine learning. Each landmark is represented by its x, y, and z coordinates, and these values are combined to form a feature vector.
The module flattens the coordinates of all landmarks into a single array, creating a structured dataset that can be used for training and inference. This transformation is essential for enabling the machine learning model to process the data effectively. The quality of the extracted features directly influences the accuracy of shot classification and posture evaluation.
\subsection{Machine Learning Module}
The machine learning module is responsible for classifying cricket shots based on the extracted features. It uses a Random Forest classifier trained on data derived from cricket shot videos. The model learns patterns associated with correct batting techniques and uses this knowledge to make predictions during analysis.
In addition to the trained model, the system employs rule-based logic to classify shots based on elbow angle thresholds. This hybrid approach ensures both accuracy and interpretability. The machine learning module outputs the predicted shot type, which is included in the final feedback provided to the user.
\subsection{Biomechanical Analysis Module}
The biomechanical analysis module focuses on evaluating the physical aspects of the player’s posture. It calculates joint angles, particularly the elbow angle, using trigonometric functions. By analyzing the relationship between the shoulder, elbow, and wrist, the module determines the degree of arm extension during the shot.
The module also examines other posture-related parameters, such as head alignment and knee balance, to identify deviations from ideal technique. These calculations provide a scientific basis for evaluating performance and form the foundation for feedback generation. This module bridges the gap between raw data and meaningful interpretation.
\subsection{Feedback Generation Module}
The feedback generation module translates analytical results into user-friendly suggestions. It combines outputs from the biomechanical analysis and machine learning modules to generate meaningful feedback. The system identifies issues such as improper head positioning or imbalance in body posture and provides corrective recommendations.
If the posture is found to be stable, the system acknowledges it with positive reinforcement. Additionally, the module integrates with the OpenAI API to generate concise technical tips, further enhancing the quality of feedback. This module plays a vital role in making the system practical and useful for users.
\subsection{Report Generation Module}
The report generation module is responsible for creating a structured PDF document containing the analysis results. It uses the ReportLab library to format the content, including shot type, average elbow angle, number of frames processed, and feedback messages.
The generated report provides a professional summary of the analysis, which can be downloaded and used for further review or training purposes. This module ensures that the results are not only displayed on the interface but also preserved in a portable and shareable format.
\subsection{Database Module}
The database module manages data storage and retrieval for the system. It is implemented using SQLite and accessed through SQLAlchemy. The module stores user information, including usernames, emails, and passwords, as well as analysis reports associated with each user.
Each report entry contains details such as the video path, report path, and shot classification. This allows users to access their previous analyses and track their progress over time. The database module ensures data persistence and supports the overall functionality of the system.

\section{Data Flow Diagrams}
The Data Flow Diagram (DFD) for the Posture-Based Detection and Feedback System illustrates the transformation of raw video input into structured biomechanical intelligence across the "Sense-Verify-Advise" pipeline. At the external level, the flow begins when the User uploads a cricket shot video via the FastAPI dashboard, which is then ingested into the system's temporary storage to trigger the analysis sequence. This raw data is first passed to the MediaPipe Pose engine, where it is decomposed from pixel arrays into a set of 33 3D skeletal landmarks (x,y,z).

