\chapter{Tools \& Technologies Used}

\section{Foundations of Computer Vision \& Data Ingestion}
\begin{sloppypar}

\subsection{System Environment and Hardware Constraints}
The system is engineered as a Post-Processing Biomechanical Engine. Unlike real-time sensor-based systems, this architecture is designed to ingest pre-recorded athletic data, allowing for deeper heuristic analysis without the latency constraints of live streaming.
\begin{itemize}
    \item {Processing Unit:} A multi-core CPU (Intel Core i5/i7 or AMD Ryzen 5/7) is utilized to manage the high-computational load of decoding uploaded MP4/AVI files and running concurrent AI inference.
\end{itemize}
\begin{itemize}
    \item Memory Management: 8GB DDR4 RAM is the baseline requirement to maintain the "Upload-Buffer Pipeline." This ensures that large video files can be held in temporary memory during landmark extraction without system crashes.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Kinematic Coordinate Extraction via Google MediaPipe}
Once the frames are stabilized by OpenCV, they are passed to Google MediaPipe. Unlike traditional heat-map-based pose estimators, MediaPipe utilizes a "BlazePose" research model that provides 33 3D landmarks. This is critical for our "Spatial Topological Mapping." The report should explain how MediaPipe maps the human body into a skeletal graph. By extracting $(x, y, z)$ coordinates, the system moves beyond 2D image analysis into 3D kinematic space, allowing the software to "understand" depth—such as whether a user’s knee is buckling inward during a squat, even when viewed from the front.
\end{sloppypar}
\section{Mathematical Modeling \& Spatial Intelligence}
\begin{sloppypar}
\subsection{Translating Landmarks into Biometric Data}
This page focuses on the transformation of raw spatial coordinates into "Deterministic Scalars." The system identifies key "Joint Triads" (e.g., Shoulder-Hip-Knee). Using the spatial data from MediaPipe, we calculate the vectors between these points. The primary objective here is to derive the internal angles of the human frame to determine if a specific posture meets the "Safe Range of Motion" (ROM).
\subsection{Geometric Calculations and Vector Analysis}
To calculate the angle $\theta$ at a specific joint, the system implements the Law of Cosines or the Dot Product of two vectors. If we define vector $\vec{a}$ as the segment from the hip to the knee, and vector $\vec{b}$ as the segment from the knee to the ankle, the angle is derived as:$$\theta = \arccos\left(\frac{\vec{a} \cdot \vec{b}}{|\vec{a}| |\vec{b}|}\right)$$This section of the report documents how these calculations are performed 30 times per second, creating a continuous stream of biometric data that describes the user's physical state with mathematical precision.
\section{Supervised Learning \& Action Benchmarking}
\subsection{Scikit-Learn and the Random Forest Paradigm}
While geometric angles provide raw data, they do not inherently "know" if a squat is deep enough or if a back is rounded. For this, we implement a Supervised Random Forest Classifier via Scikit-Learn. This model was chosen for its robustness against "noisy" data—common in home-workout environments with cluttered backgrounds. The Random Forest operates on an ensemble of decision trees, taking the calculated angles as input features and outputting a classification (e.g., "Correct Form," "Rounded Back," or "Incomplete Range").

\subsection{Empirical Benchmarking with UCF101}
To ensure the classifier is scientifically grounded, the UCF101 Dataset is employed as the benchmark. UCF101 is a massive action recognition dataset containing over 13,000 videos across 101 categories. By using this as a "Ground Truth" training set, the system's ability to recognize complex human movements is validated against industry-standard benchmarks. This section discusses the training-validation split and the resulting confusion matrix used to tune the system's accuracy.
\end{sloppypar}
\section{Generative Inference \& Feedback Translation}
\begin{sloppypar}
\subsection{OpenAI GPT-4o: From Data to Coaching}A major innovation in this project is the transition from "Binary Classification" to "Generative Coaching." Using the OpenAI GPT-4o API, the system performs Zero-shot Generative Inference. It takes the deterministic scalars (e.g., "Back angle is $15^\circ$ off-parallel") and translates them into human-centric coaching heuristics. This prevents the system from sounding like a machine; instead of saying "Error 402," it says, "Keep your chest up and look forward to align your spine.\subsection{Heuristic Mapping and Prompt Engineering}This section documents the "System Prompting" strategy. The API is fed the current biometric state and the historical movement data. GPT-4o acts as the "Intelligence Layer," synthesizing the ML classification and the raw geometric data into a concise, encouraging feedback loop. This mimics the behavior of a professional personal trainer, providing corrective cues in real-time.
\end{sloppypar}
\section{Backend Infrastructure \& Concurrency}
\begin{sloppypar}
\subsection{FastAPI: The Asynchronous Core}
The backend is powered by FastAPI, an ASGI (Asynchronous Server Gateway Interface) framework. This is critical because video processing is "I/O Bound" and "CPU Bound." Using async and await syntax, FastAPI allows the system to process incoming video frames while simultaneously communicating with the GPT-4o API and the SQLite database. This section explains the benefit of Uvicorn as the lightning-fast web server that manages these concurrent worker processes.

\subsection{RESTful Architecture and Data Flow}
The report details the API design:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item POST /analyze: Ingests video frames and returns skeletal landmarks.
\end{enumerate}

\begin{enumerate}
    \item GET /history: Retrieves previous session stats from the database.
\end{enumerate}

\begin{enumerate}
    \item POST /generate-feedback: Triggers the GPT-4o heuristic translation.
\end{enumerate}
By decoupling the "Vision" layer from the "Logic" layer, the system maintains high performance even on consumer-grade hardware.
\end{sloppypar}
\section{State Management \& UI Aesthetics}
\subsection{SQLite: Relational State and Security}
For data persistence, SQLite is utilized to store user profiles, session logs, and movement history. This choice ensures a lightweight footprint without the overhead of a managed database server. The report highlights the "Secure, HTTP-only" session isolation, ensuring that a user's biometric data—which is highly sensitive—is isolated at the database level and protected from Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) attacks.

\subsection{Tailwind CSS and Glassmorphism UI}
The frontend utilizes Tailwind CSS, focusing on a Glassmorphism design paradigm. This aesthetic choice (using backdrop-blur and semi-transparent layers) is not purely visual; it allows the coaching feedback to be overlaid on the video stream without obscuring the user's view of their own body. This section discusses the "UX of Feedback"—how color-coded skeletal overlays (Green for correct, Red for error) provide immediate subconscious cues to the user.


\section{Auditing \& Programmatic Reporting}
\begin{sloppypar}
\subsection{ReportLab: Immutable Biometric Auditing}
The final component of the stack is ReportLab, used for Programmatic PDF Serialization. At the end of a session, the system aggregates all movement data, coaching cues, and accuracy scores. ReportLab then generates an "Immutable Biometric Audit"—a tamper-proof PDF report. This is essential for professional applications where a user might need to share their progress with a physical therapist or doctor.
\subsection{System Integration and Future Scalability}
The concluding section of the Tools and Technologies chapter explains how these 10 distinct technologies integrate into a "Feedback Loop." It discusses the "End-to-End Latency" (from camera to GPT feedback) and provides a roadmap for scalability, such as moving the processing to the "Edge" or utilizing WebSockets for even faster real-time interaction.
\end{sloppypar}
