\section{Summary of Results}
\begin{sloppypar}
The results of the Posture-Based Detection and Feedback System for Cricket demonstrate a successful integration of high-speed computer vision and generative artificial intelligence to provide professional-grade athletic coaching. By utilizing a "Triple-Model" architecture, the system achieves objective biomechanical analysis that was previously restricted to expensive motion-capture laboratories.

\subsection*{Core Technical Outcomes}
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Precision Landmark Extraction}: The system successfully extracts 33 distinct 3D skeletal landmarks using Google MediaPipe, allowing for a digital "Spatial Topological Mapping" of the athlete's body.
    \item \textbf{Biometric Accuracy}: Through the application of the Law of Cosines, the system calculates joint angles (such as elbow extension) in real-time with mathematical precision.
    \item \textbf{Automated Shot Classification}: Using a Random Forest classifier trained on the UCF101 dataset, the system accurately categorizes strokes into types like "Lofted Drive," "Cover Drive," or "Defensive Stroke" based on kinematic signatures.
    \item \textbf{Generative Coaching Heuristics}: The integration of OpenAI GPT-4o allows the system to translate raw scalar data into human-centric coaching tips, such as "Keep your head level" or "Balance your weight," effectively eliminating human observation bias.
Based on the cumulative analysis of the three test cases, the system demonstrates a high level of consistency in detecting biomechanical metrics across different shot types and video conditions. By processing a total of 1,965 frames across the three samples, the system successfully identified diverse stroke categories—including Close-Body Blocks and Pull/Hook Shots—while maintaining high-frequency skeletal tracking.
